eaning either ‘beloved man’ (from <i>dēore</i> ‘dear, beloved’) or ‘fierce, spirited man’ (from <i>dēor</i> ‘wild creature’). See   Dear  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Duibhdhiorma</b> ‘descendant of <i>Duibhdhiorma</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘black trooper’, see   Dormer  . There has been some confusion with the more common personal name <i>Diarmaid</i> (see   McDermott   and compare   Dearmond  ).","Probably an Americanized form of German <b>Diermann</b> or <b>Thiermann</b>, which derive from short forms of the personal name   Dietrich   or perhaps from Middle High German <i>tier</i> ‘animal, game’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’ and thus denote a game or venison dealer."]},{"name":"Dorer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Oskar.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by the gate of a town or city, from Middle High German <i>tōr(e)</i>, Middle Low German <i>dore</i> ‘gate’, + the suffix <i>-(e)r</i>, denoting an inhabitant; alternatively, an occupational name for a gate keeper. See   Dorman   2."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Dorman was born in 1490, in Warmsworth, Yorkshire, England, his father, George Dorman of Malpas, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth Johns, was 20. He married Ann Elizabeth DeKleves before 1520. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1540, in Warmsworth, South Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1490–1540":"1490–1540","1510–1601":"1510–1601","1500–1601":"1500–1601","1465–1550":"1465–1550","1470–Female":"1470–Surnud","1601":"1601","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","Bef 1520":"enne 1520","1465":"1465","1540":"1540","1550":"1550","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Warmsworth, South Yorkshire, England":"Warmsworth, South Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warmsw